- VSCode Version: 1.5.3
- OS Version: OSX 10.10.5

Steps to Reproduce:

Create an extension command that runs the following code:

```
let disposable = vscode.commands.registerCommand('myExt.testCommand', function() {

    // Get active text editor
    let textEditor = vscode.window.activeTextEditor;

    // Ignore if no active TextEditor
    if (typeof(textEditor) === 'undefined') {
      return false;
    }

    // Print out the current selections in the document
    console.log(textEditor.selections);

    let text = "helloworld";

    // Create an edit to insert into the document
    let edits = [
      vscode.TextEdit.insert(textEditor.selection.active, text)
    ];

    // Insert the text
    let uri = textEditor.document.uri;
    let edit = new vscode.WorkspaceEdit();
    edit.set(uri, edits);
    vscode.workspace.applyEdit(edit);

    // Once again, print out the current selections
    console.log(textEditor.selections);

    return true;
}
```

So essentially this code, prints out your current selections to the debug console, then inserts some text where the primary/active cursor is, then again, prints out your current selections.

What you will find is that the differences between the 2 selections that get printed to the debug console are exactly the same even though your selections have changed. When you `.insert()` text into the document, that text is then automatically selected. 

For example if you run this command, `helloworld` is inserted into the document. Then if you immediately type a letter or backspace or whatever, `helloworld` is replaced with whatever you typed, just as if `helloworld` was selected already (like if you selected it using your mouse). The bug is that your inserted text is selected, but it doesn't appear to immediately appear as part of `TextEditor.selections`.

Sorry if this is a bit confusing. I assume this is a bug. Can anyone confirm or deny this?
